<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-06-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-06-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="99" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d99">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.51/949.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador to
                                    Germany</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-06-17">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 17, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The German Government is strongly of the opinion that there must be no
                            deviation from the attitude assumed toward Russia and Japan; that is to
                            say, we can recognize in them only such special rights and privileges in
                            Mongolia and Manchuria as they may have acquired by formal treaties or
                            conventions with the old Chinese Government.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Leishman</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>